Certainly! In JavaScript, you can use try-catch blocks for basic error handling during API calls. Here's an example using async/await syntax:

```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Network response was not ok.');
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('There was a problem with the fetch operation:', error);
  }
}
fetchData();
```

This code attempts to make an API call and processes the response. If there's an issue with the network request or if the server returns an error status code, it will catch these exceptions and log them accordingly. Remember to replace 'https://api.example.com/data' with your actual API endpoint. Also, ensure proper error handling according to your application's needs. Let me know if you need further assistance!
